<file path="content/pages/eupothic.md">
---
title: "Euphotic Zone"
layout: "presentation"
summary: "The Sunlight Zone — surface to 200 meters. Where the ocean glows green-blue and almost everything you've ever seen on a nature show lives."
order: 1
seo:
  title: "Euphotic Zone — The Sunlight Layer"
  description: "Surface to 200 meters. Photosynthesis, phytoplankton, and the bulk of marine life all live in this thin lit layer."
---

## Where the light still reaches

You're floating just below the surface. Above you: sky. Below you: 200 meters of water that sunlight can still punch through. This thin band — the top 5% of the average ocean's depth — is where roughly **90% of marine species** live.

The word *euphotic* comes from Greek: *eu* (well) + *photos* (light). Well-lit. Everything down here runs on sunlight, directly or one trophic level removed.

## What lives here

```stat-grid
~90% | of marine species
200 m | depth limit of photosynthesis
~50% | of Earth's oxygen produced here
~15 °C | average surface temperature
```

Phytoplankton drift in the upper meters and do most of that oxygen-making. Zooplankton graze on them. Schooling fish — sardines, anchovies, mackerel — eat the zooplankton. Tuna and sharks eat the schooling fish. Dolphins, sea lions, and most whales feed in this layer or pass through it. Sea turtles cruise it. Jellyfish pulse along on currents. Coral reefs, despite living on the seafloor, only exist where that seafloor is shallow enough to stay inside the euphotic zone — they need the sun.

## Why it matters

If the euphotic zone collapsed, the rest of the ocean would follow within a few decades. Every layer below depends on dead and dying organic matter drifting down from here — what oceanographers call **marine snow**. The deep ocean is, in a real sense, fed by leftovers from the sunlight zone.

## Keep going

The light is about to fade. Below 200 meters, photosynthesis stops being possible. Welcome to twilight.

[Descend to the Dysphotic Zone →](/dysphotic)
</file>

